article.description: Vickie Johnson scored 21 points and Becky Hammon made three 3-pointers to help the New York Liberty finally beat the Detroit Shock, 72-69 on Sunday.
article.headline: Late free throws ice game for Liberty
article.linkText: Liberty nearly squander lead, hang on against Shock
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Vickie Johnson kept Deanna Nolan and the Detroit
Shock from making it three in a row against the New York Liberty.

Johnson scored 21 points and made sure Nolan stayed busy
defending her, while Becky Hammon made three 3-pointers to help New
York finally beat the Shock this season, 72-69 Sunday. Hammon and
Shameka Christon each made a pair of key free throws down the
stretch to help the Liberty (3-4) hang on.

Nolan, the Liberty's undoing in two earlier losses, scored 16
points, but missed a tying 3-pointer late in the game.

"I wanted Nolan to not only play offense, but play defense
too," said Johnson, who made 8-of-16 shots. "In Detroit, I only
took four shots."

In that game, a 68-66 loss last week, Nolan scored 12 of her 34
points in overtime. Last month, she made five key free throws down
the stretch at Madison Square Garden.

Nolan nearly did it again Sunday.

She cut the Liberty's lead to a point with 19 seconds to play,
but Christon made two free throws and Nolan missed a 3 and Ruth
Riley missed a leaning 3-pointer at the buzzer after the Liberty
successfully defended an inbounds play designed to give Nolan a
shot.

"They switched that well," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said.
"Ruth is a very fine 3-point shooter for somebody her size. That
was our other option, that she gets the ball and maybe gets an open
look. They played sound defense, got to give them credit there."

Cheryl Ford had 17 points and 11 rebounds for Detroit (5-2),
tying a team record with her sixth straight game of 10 rebounds or
more.

Ann Wauters had 12 points and 11 rebounds for the Liberty, which
made all nine of its free throws in the second half and missed only
two.

New York trailed 30-29 at halftime and took control midway
through the second half. Elena Baranova, who struggled offensively,
made a 3-pointer and a jumper. Then Hammon drained a long 3-pointer
with 12:20 remaining, and followed up with two more 3s for a 55-44
lead with just under 10 minutes to play.

The Shock closed to 64-59, making 10-of-14 free throws along the
way. But Wauters made a layup and Baranova, who finished with 11
points, made a pair of free throws to help New York extend its
lead.

"You know, in the seven games we've played, it has been like
this," New York coach Pat Coyle said. "There aren't going to be
any blowouts. Every game goes down to the wire and we're beginning
to understand that."
